  "prompt": "What is distance over time?",
  "response": "\"Distance over time\" typically refers to the concept of speed, which is a measure of how fast an object is moving. Specifically, speed is calculated by dividing the distance traveled by the time it takes to travel that distance. The formula for speed is:\n\n\\[ \\text{Speed} = \\frac{\\text{Distance}}{\\text{Time}} \\]\n\n### Key Points:\n1. **Distance**: The total length of the path traveled by an object, usually measured in units like meters (m), kilometers (km), miles (mi), etc.\n2. **Time**: The duration over which the distance is covered, usually measured in units like seconds (s), minutes (min), hours (h), etc.\n3. **Speed**: The rate at which an object covers distance, typically measured in units like meters per second (m/s), kilometers per hour (km/h), miles per hour (mph), etc.\n\n### Example:\nIf a car travels 100 kilometers in 2 hours, the speed of the car is:\n\n\\[ \\text{Speed} = \\frac{100 \\text{ km}}{2 \\text{ h}} = 50 \\text{ km/h} \\]\n\nThis means the car is moving at a speed of 50 kilometers per hour.\n\n### Related Concepts:\n- **Velocity**: Similar to speed, but it also includes the direction of motion.\n- **Average Speed**: The total distance traveled divided by the total time taken.\n- **Instantaneous Speed**: The speed of an object at a specific moment in time.\n\nUnderstanding \"distance over time\" is fundamental in physics, engineering, and everyday life, as it helps in analyzing and predicting the motion of objects.",
